  <h1>Overview: What is it?</h1>
      <p>An incentive the government provides to encourage innovation, research, and development in the United States.</p>

        <p>Companies that conduct research and development (R&D) activities are allowed to capture a portion of the R&D expenses incurred as a tax credit.</p>
            
        <p>The company can use the credit to directly offset its tax liability.</p>

    <h1>The Need for a Specialist</h1>
    <ul>An R&D Credit project involves:</ul>
    <li>Determining what business activities and expenses qualify as R&D under tax law rules.</li> 
    <li> Extracting, manipulating, and analyzing company data sets to ensure expenses have been properly included in (or excluded from) the credit calculation.</li>
    <li>Documenting the companyâ€™s R&D activities and the qualification and quantification process to ensure the claim can be justified in the event of a tax audit. </li>

    <ul>Companies usually hire 3rd party consultants because the credit is: </ul>
    <li>Niche: requires knowledge of R&D Credit rules and industry/company specific knowledge.</li>
    <li>Complex and sometimes ambiguous: often resulting in an over-claiming or under-claiming of the credit.</li>
    <li>Heavily scrutinized: inadequate documentation can open companies up to consequences associated with erroneous (or in extreme cases, fraudulent) tax claims.</li>
